{"id":"d=origam-topic-4404//p=c02b659cdbc946e4bc0e8e3f9552e451","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4404"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["8fadd9b162b14088bf2bc2ed9f13c06e"],"__file_part":["75f8ee724c834cca976fbd4c126015d9"],"__part_n":["0"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["4404"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-adjust-ux-ui-of-the-client-application/4404"],"title":["How to adjust UX/UI of the client application"],"imagesFound":["11"],"imagesDescribed":["11"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a388424a98f0d8b427f4923d6521d3f2a645bdd5.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/ed5dca9cd0482563fce3dabab006bff3e46ec28e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b1b8d45cb8dff3797401bff08eb677f59c059a67.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/083f1cf3377ad4441cc8bdf267b814e121f275ee.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4b6cbd4641981a6580362124f2208a5e042f2a3e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ffc5c8703e2f6dd56a18661ee9098cdbb64c11f7.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/757f508ecacc20fc28a5bb41fbcb2bd2cb09e9d0.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/40d3044d81054f4189021fce51d605019fa13edf.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0bc90246bb802c4f770ac7426df4e34c010ea9c5.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/57b4ebb877107c4565dc52e95058ec6daebfef62.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8a565e0e2c67e7348fc83de8b7795515a49bf01a.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# How to adjust UX/UI of the client application\n\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-adjust-ux-ui-of-the-client-application/4404\n\n@vikter (2026-03-05 12:39:52Z):\n   \n This article shows how to fine-tune various UX/UI details in your client application by editing its model. Additional settings options will be gradually added here. \n   Date field format in the form grid view \n If you want to switch from this \n \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a388424a98f0d8b427f4923d6521d3f2a645bdd5.png]\nDescription: The image displays a table listing due dates with a single column labeled \u0022Due date.\u0022 The visible dates include: 02/28/2026 00:00:00, 03/10/2026 00:00:00, 03/25/2026 00:00:00, 03/31/2026 00:00:00, and 02/15/2026 00:00:00. The table appears to be used for tracking deadlines or scheduled events, presenting the dates in a format that includes both date and time.\n\n\n  \n to this \n  \n go to the screen section where the date field is located and change the  Format  property to  Short  or any other format you prefer: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/ed5dca9cd0482563fce3dabab006bff3e46ec28e.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a property editor interface for a component named \u0022AsDateBox4\u0022 within an ORIGAM GUI framework. In the \u0022Properties\u0022 section, several categories are visible, including \u0022Behavior,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022Design,\u0022 \u0022Layout,\u0022 and \u0022Misc.\u0022 Under \u0022Misc,\u0022 there are fields labeled \u0022CustomFormat,\u0022 \u0022DateValue,\u0022 and \u0022Format,\u0022 with \u0022Format\u0022 set to \u0022Long.\u0022 Additional fields include \u0022HideOnForm,\u0022 \u0022ReadOnly,\u0022 and \u0022Style,\u0022 where \u0022HideOnForm\u0022 is also set to \u0022Long.\u0022 This interface is intended for configuring the properties of a date input component in an application.\n\n\n  \n To have both the date and time without seconds, set  Format  property to  Custom  and fill  CustomFormat  property with the desired date format, e.g.  MM/dd/yyyy HH:mm . More on custom date and time formats can be found  here . \n   Default order of form columns \n If you want to place columns in a form (both in grid view and form view) in a specific order, you need to change the  TabIndex  property of the fields in the screen section where they are used. \n  TabIndex  determines the order in which you navigate through the fields in form view using the  Tab  key, as well as the order in which they are displayed in the grid view. \n To change the order, go to your screen section. There you can either set it manually for each element in  Properties , or in the editor click on the screen section and press  Ctrl \u002B Shift \u002B T  (in Microsoft Windows). White numbers with a blue background will appear in the top-left corner of each element. Click the elements in the desired order (already selected elements will change to a blue number with a white background), and then press  Ctrl \u002B Shift \u002B T  again. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b1b8d45cb8dff3797401bff08eb677f59c059a67.png]\nDescription: Screen Section: Status is displayed, indicating a configuration interface for a data source titled \u0022Status.\u0022 The interface includes fields with the following labels: Data Source, Name, and Id, along with corresponding values such as \u0022Status,\u0022 \u00222ea39521-161e-4e0c-b04a-9c68836d6e.\u0022 In the right panel, three fields labeled Order, Name, and Color are present, with the values 0, 1, and 2 entered respectively. The Package is identified as \u0022taskman,\u0022 and there is a Toolbox section visible in the layout but not detailed. The interface appears to be part of a higher-level software tool for managing or configuring data sources.\n\n\n  \n If there is any issue with the order or another problem with the columns, e.g. when you add a new column and it shows in the last place, you can reset the configuration. Right-click the screen menu item and choose  Reset Column Configuration . \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.","vecto